üß† JavaScript Declaration Assignments
1Ô∏è‚É£ Declare 4 variables in the same line
let a = 10, b = 20, c = 30, d = 40;
console.log(a, b, c, d);


‚úÖ You can declare and initialize multiple variables separated by commas.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Find the wrong variable naming conventions
// ‚úÖ Correct
let firstName;
let _age;
let $price;
let totalMarks;

// ‚ùå Incorrect
let 1name;         // ‚ùå starts with number
let my-name;       // ‚ùå hyphen not allowed
let var;           // ‚ùå reserved keyword
let first name;    // ‚ùå space not allowed


‚úÖ Variables can only start with a letter, _, or $ ‚Äî and cannot use reserved words.

3Ô∏è‚É£ What happens if we declare the same variable name multiple times
var x = 10;
var x = 20;  // ‚úÖ allowed with 'var'
console.log(x); // Output: 20

let y = 10;
// let y = 20; // ‚ùå Error: Identifier 'y' has already been declared


üß© var allows redeclaration;
let and const do not.

4Ô∏è‚É£ What happens if we assign value to an undeclared variable
x = 100;
console.log(x);


‚úÖ Works, but creates a global variable implicitly (bad practice).
If you use "use strict";, it will throw an error.

5Ô∏è‚É£ What error occurs by printing undeclared variable
console.log(a);


‚ùå Error:

ReferenceError: a is not defined

6Ô∏è‚É£ Declare a variable with string literal using single and double quotes
let name1 = 'Edupoly';
let name2 = "Hyderabad";
console.log(name1, name2);


‚úÖ Both ' ' and " " work for strings in JavaScript.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Declare a variable in script.html

script.html

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Script Variable</title>
</head>
<body>
  <script>
    let course = "JavaScript";
  </script>
</body>
</html>

8Ô∏è‚É£ Print the variable value in script.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Print Variable</title>
</head>
<body>
  <script>
    let course = "JavaScript";
    document.write(course);
  </script>
</body>
</html>


‚úÖ Output on webpage ‚Üí
JavaScript

9Ô∏è‚É£ Declare two variables and print the addition.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Addition Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <script>
    let a = 10, b = 20;
    let sum = a + b;
    document.write("Sum = " + sum);
  </script>
</body>
</html>


‚úÖ Output: Sum = 30

üîü Declare a variable with string literal.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>String Literal Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <script>
    let message = "Welcome to Edupoly";
    document.write(message);
  </script>
</body>
</html>

11Ô∏è‚É£ Program: Read first name, last name & year of birth
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Display Name and Year</title>
</head>
<body>
  <script>
    let firstName = prompt("Input your firstname:");
    let lastName = prompt("Input your lastname:");
    let year = prompt("Input your year of birth:");
    document.write(firstName + " " + lastName + " born on " + year);
  </script>
</body>
</html>


‚úÖ Example Output:

Tom Davis born on 1982

‚úÖ Summary Table
Task	Key Concept	Example
Declare multiple vars	let a=1,b=2,c=3	Multiple assignment
Invalid names	Reserved words, numbers first	let 1x ‚ùå
Redeclare variable	Allowed for var only	var a=1; var a=2;
Undeclared variable	Becomes global	x=5;
Print undeclared var	ReferenceError	console.log(y)
String literals	'Edupoly' / "Edupoly"	‚úÖ
Prompt input	prompt("Enter name")	User input
Output	console.log() or document.write()	Display data
